<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8" standalone="yes"?><rss version="2.0" xmlns:atom="http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom" xmlns:content="http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/"><channel><title>Tutorial on ilManzo's blog</title><link>https://ilmanzo.github.io/tags/tutorial/</link><description>Recent content in Tutorial on ilManzo's blog</description><generator>Hugo</generator><language>en-us</language><copyright>2012-2025 Andrea Manzini</copyright><lastBuildDate>Sun, 03 May 2026 00:00:00 +0000</lastBuildDate><atom:link href="https://ilmanzo.github.io/tags/tutorial/index.xml" rel="self" type="application/rss+xml"/><item><title>Flatpak: unboxing the sandbox</title><link>https://ilmanzo.github.io/post/flatpak-unboxing-guide/</link><pubDate>Sun, 03 May 2026 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://ilmanzo.github.io/post/flatpak-unboxing-guide/</guid><description>How to have new apps without letting the dependency mess leak onto your carpet</description></item><item><title>Rootless Podman as a Salt Lab Environment</title><link>https://ilmanzo.github.io/post/rootless_podman_as_salt_lab_environment/</link><pubDate>Wed, 18 Mar 2026 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://ilmanzo.github.io/post/rootless_podman_as_salt_lab_environment/</guid><description>&lt;h2 id="-salt-without-the-sudo"&gt;🧂 Salt without the sudo&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Follow-up from &lt;a href="https://ilmanzo.github.io/post/podman_quadlets_tutorial/"&gt;the previous post&lt;/a&gt;, today we are going to put our systemd-managed containers to work and use them for some useful tasks.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The idea is to set up an environment to learn how the configuration management &lt;a href="https://saltproject.io/"&gt;Salt&lt;/a&gt; works, and play/hack around with it, without even needing root or &lt;code&gt;sudo&lt;/code&gt; rights. After all, in the infra-world, &lt;strong&gt;the Salt must flow&lt;/strong&gt;!&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;So we will setup two containers, one as a &lt;em&gt;salt server&lt;/em&gt; and the other as a &lt;em&gt;salt &amp;ldquo;minion&amp;rdquo;&lt;/em&gt; (representing the machine that will be configured via salt).&lt;/p&gt;</description></item><item><title>A Friendly Guide to Podman Quadlets</title><link>https://ilmanzo.github.io/post/podman_quadlets_tutorial/</link><pubDate>Tue, 03 Feb 2026 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://ilmanzo.github.io/post/podman_quadlets_tutorial/</guid><description>&lt;h2 id="-hi-geekos"&gt;🦎 Hi geekos!&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;p&gt;If you’ve been running containers on your &lt;a href="https://get.opensuse.org/leap"&gt;Leap&lt;/a&gt; or &lt;a href="https://get.opensuse.org/tumbleweed/"&gt;Tumbleweed&lt;/a&gt; machine, you probably started with &lt;code&gt;podman run&lt;/code&gt; commands. Maybe you moved to &lt;code&gt;Docker Compose&lt;/code&gt; files to manage stacks. Those are great tools, but they have a limitation, as they don&amp;rsquo;t integrate natively with &lt;code&gt;systemd&lt;/code&gt;, your operating system&amp;rsquo;s init system.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;When your server reboots, do your containers start back up automatically? If a container crashes, does it restart? How do you view its logs alongside your system journal?&lt;/p&gt;</description></item><item><title>A Headless Linux Router Build</title><link>https://ilmanzo.github.io/post/repurpose_old_netbook_as_wifi_repeater/</link><pubDate>Sat, 24 Jan 2026 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://ilmanzo.github.io/post/repurpose_old_netbook_as_wifi_repeater/</guid><description>&lt;h2 id="-void-in-the-basement"&gt;👻 Void in the Basement&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;p&gt;I have a basement, and I have a problem: no WiFi signal in said basement. I have also a piece of e-waste that refuses to die: a &lt;a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Samsung_N130"&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Samsung N130 netbook from 2009&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/a&gt;.
It has a single-core Atom processor and 1GB of RAM. By modern standards, it can barely open a web browser. But for a Linux terminal, It&amp;rsquo;s a &lt;em&gt;supercomputer&lt;/em&gt;.
Instead of buying a generic ~10€ WiFi repeater, I decided to turn this little warrior into a fully programmable, secure, and transparent WiFi router using &lt;a href="https://voidlinux.org/"&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Void Linux&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/a&gt;. Here is exactly how I did it.&lt;/p&gt;</description></item><item><title>From QEMU Headache to Headless</title><link>https://ilmanzo.github.io/post/qboot-qemu-helper/</link><pubDate>Sun, 28 Sep 2025 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://ilmanzo.github.io/post/qboot-qemu-helper/</guid><description>Taming a Command-Line Monster</description></item><item><title>How much code are you testing ? (3)</title><link>https://ilmanzo.github.io/post/pintool-function-tracing/</link><pubDate>Tue, 17 Jun 2025 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://ilmanzo.github.io/post/pintool-function-tracing/</guid><description>Using Intel PIN to measure test coverage on binaries</description></item><item><title>How much code are you testing ? (2)</title><link>https://ilmanzo.github.io/post/measuring-test-coverage-on-binaries/</link><pubDate>Sun, 30 Mar 2025 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://ilmanzo.github.io/post/measuring-test-coverage-on-binaries/</guid><description>Measuring test coverage on binaries</description></item><item><title>How much code are you testing ? (1)</title><link>https://ilmanzo.github.io/post/measuring-coverage-of-integration-tests/</link><pubDate>Sun, 23 Feb 2025 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://ilmanzo.github.io/post/measuring-coverage-of-integration-tests/</guid><description>Measuring coverage of integration tests</description></item><item><title>Systemd Socket Activation Explained</title><link>https://ilmanzo.github.io/post/systemd-socket-activated-services/</link><pubDate>Sun, 02 Feb 2025 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://ilmanzo.github.io/post/systemd-socket-activated-services/</guid><description>Stop Wasting Resources: how to start your services on demand</description></item><item><title>The Linux kernel ftrace</t